<HEADLINE>
<P>
WOMAN KIDNAPED, RAPED, BEATEN BY 2 CLAIMING TO BE GANG MEMBERS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From a Times Staff Writer 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
HUNTINGTON BEACH 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
A 19-year-old woman was kidnaped, raped and beaten early Monday by two armed 
men who identified themselves to her as gang members from Los Angeles County, 
police said. 
</P>
<P>
"When they released her, they said that by not killing her, that was their 
Christmas present to her," Police Lt. Ed McErlain said. 
</P>
<P>
The woman was walking from her car through the parking lot of her apartment 
complex when the men approached and asked directions, police said. 
</P>
<P>
"She attempted to run from the men, but they grabbed her and struck her in the 
face several times and forced her into their vehicle at gunpoint," McErlain 
said. 
</P>
<P>
They held her captive for about an hour, beat her repeatedly and raped her, he 
said. Both men had guns. 
</P>
<P>
After she was released, the woman went to a nearby home and called police. She 
was taken to a local hospital, where she was treated for a possibly broken 
nose, McErlain said. 
</P>
<P>
McErlain said one assailant was described as Samoan-American, about 22, 5 feet, 
7 inches tall and 200 pounds, with brown hair. The other was described as a 
stocky Latino, about 22 and 200 pounds, with brown hair. The victim described 
their car as a "four-door, shiny blue compact." 
</P>
</TEXT>
<SUBJECT>
<P>
